When you create a blueprint in&nbsp;VCF Automation, the resource type palette includes a number of default resource types. You might have use cases where you want to create blueprints based on an expanded list of resource types. You can create custom resource types, add them to the design canvas, and create blueprints that support your design and deployment needs.Before you begin, ensure that a&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;instance is associated with your organization.As an organization administrator, you have two ways to create custom resources. VCF Operations orchestrator &nbsp;inventory type. &nbsp;You can create custom resources based on existing&nbsp; VCF Operations orchestrator &nbsp;inventory objects, with or without leveraging the Dynamic Types plug-in for&nbsp; VCF Operations orchestrator . Dynamic type is required if the desired resource does not exist out-of-the-box in&nbsp; VCF Operations orchestrator &nbsp;as a SDK inventory object type. You can expose any&nbsp; VCF Operations orchestrator &nbsp;resource type, be it native, provided by a plug-in in&nbsp; VCF Operations orchestrator , or created using the Dynamic Types plug-in. New schema . You can define custom resource types that are based on workflows with any kind of input and output. Every input and output becomes part of the schema and its value is shown in the deployment. Because this custom resource type is based on your own custom outputs instead of&nbsp; VCF Operations orchestrator &nbsp;inventory objects, you must provide a READ workflow in addition to the Create and Delete workflows. You also define what inputs that workflow has. For the Read and Delete workflows, you can map the inputs and outputs to schema properties. This is necessary because the schema property names might not match the input/outputs of the Read and Delete workflows. Custom resource name and resource typeThe custom resource name identifies your custom resource inside the blueprint resource type palette.The resource type of a custom resource must begin with&nbsp;Custom.&nbsp;and each resource type must be unique. Although the inclusion of&nbsp;Custom.&nbsp;is not validated in the text box, the string is automatically added if you remove it.To add custom resources to blueprints, you must activate the custom resource. You can make the custom resource available to blueprints associated with a single project or make it available to all projects.Life cycle actions for custom resourcesYou define the following life cycle actions for your custom resources: ** Create **: this action is called when a deployment is started. ** Read **: this action is used to retrieve the latest state of the deployed resource. The READ workflow is run every few minutes to get the latest status of every provisioned custom resource. You also define what inputs that workflow has, for example, you can just pass the resource ID as an input. The Read action is required only for new schema-based custom resources. ** Destroy **: this action is called when a deployment is deleted. You can edit the&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;workflow associated with your life cycle actions by clicking the&nbsp;Change&nbsp;option for the action.VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;custom resourcesEach&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;custom resource is based on a SDK inventory type and is created by a&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;workflow that has an output which is an instance of your desired SDK type. Primitive types, such as&nbsp;Properties,&nbsp;Date,&nbsp;string, and&nbsp;number&nbsp;are not supported for the creation of custom resource types.SDK object types can be differentiated from other&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;property types by the colon (":") used to separate the plug-in name and the type name.You can use the built-in workflows in&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator, or you can create your own. You can create custom resources by clicking on the&nbsp;Resource Definition&nbsp;option in the custom resource editor and selecting&nbsp;Orchestrator inventory type.VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;custom resource inventory typeThe inventory type property defines the type of your custom resource.When you define your custom resource types, you can define the scope of the availability of the select external type. The selected external type can be: Shared across projects. Available only for the selected project. When you select a Create workflow in your custom resource type, the inventory type drop-down appears underneath it. The drop-down includes inventory type properties, that are selected from the output parameters of the&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;workflow. The selected workflow output properties included in the drop-down must be non-array SDK object types such as&nbsp;VC:VirtualMachine.When creating custom workflows that use the dynamic type plug-in, verify that their variables are defined by using the&nbsp;DynamicTypesManager.getObject()&nbsp;method.You can only have one custom resource type with a specific inventory type value per defined scope. For example, if you create a custom resource in your project that uses&nbsp;VC:VirtualMachine&nbsp;as an inventory type, you cannot create another custom resource for the same project that uses the same inventory type. You also cannot create two shared custom resources that use the same inventory type.VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;life cycle action validationWhen you add Create, Destroy, and Read workflows as life cycle actions to your custom resource,&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;validates that the selected workflows have correct input and output property definitions. The&nbsp; Create &nbsp;workflow must have an output parameter that is an SDK object type, such as&nbsp; SSH:Host &nbsp;or&nbsp; SQL:Database . If the selected workflow does not pass the validation, you cannot add Read or Destroy workflows, or save your changes to the custom resource. The Create workflow you select should output the desired type. For the old CR types(based on the Inventory), it is possible to create a deployment with CR by executing the create wf used in the CR as a Catalog item The&nbsp; Destroy &nbsp;workflow must have an input parameter that is an SDK object type that matches the inventory type of the custom resource. The&nbsp; Read &nbsp;workflow must have both an input and output parameter that is an SDK object type that matches the inventory type of the custom resource. Custom resource property schemaYou can edit and view the custom resource properties schema by selecting the&nbsp;Schema Properties&nbsp;tab. The schema includes the name, data type, property type, and, if it is available, the description of a given property. The schema also defines if a specific property is required or optional in the blueprint.When you add&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;workflows to your custom resource, their input and output parameters are added as properties.From this tab, you can also modify and format the properties of your&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator-based custom resources. For example, you can change the display name of a given property, add constraints, or make it read- or write-only for the deployment.When adding constraints to either the item section of array fields or properties section of objects fields in the properties schema, verify that you have validated these constraints as incorrectly applied constraints can cause issues with the custom resource. For example, when adding a maximum constraint to a numbers array, you must verify that this constraint does not break the property's default value.You can edit the property schema for custom resources by navigating to the&nbsp;Schema Properties&nbsp;tab and using either the&nbsp;Code&nbsp;or&nbsp;Form&nbsp;tab. Code : Edit the property schema by using YAML content. When selecting this option, the property schema is defined by using the JSON Schema. Form : Hide non-required and non-computed properties from the schema by clicking&nbsp; Remove Property . Day 2 Operation Custom Request FormsYou can streamline the request form of the day 2 operations included in your custom resource by adding and modifying different types of resource properties.For example, you can bind the value of an input parameter in your request form to an external source, such as a&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;action that retrieves a deployment name or project name. You can also bind the value of a specific input parameter to the computed value of two other text boxes included in the same request form.This functionality is available for both custom resources and resource actions. You can customize the value of the input properties of your request form from the&nbsp;Values&nbsp;tab of the&nbsp;Request Parameters&nbsp;page of the custom resource or resource action editor.Day 2 Operation Request Form ValidationYou can validate the request form of your day 2 operations by adding an external validation. By using an external validation, you prevent the user from submitting the request form until the validation parameters are satisfied. You can add external validation from the&nbsp;Validations&nbsp;tab of the&nbsp;Request Parameters&nbsp;page of the custom resource or resource action editor. After selecting the tab, you can drag an&nbsp;Orchestrator validation&nbsp;element to the canvas and add a&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;action that you want to use for validation.For example, you can create a custom resource that includes a day 2 operation for changing a user password. For such a use case, you can add a&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;action with&nbsp;newPassword&nbsp;and&nbsp;confirmPassword&nbsp;input parameters that use the&nbsp;SecureString&nbsp;type.This is a sample script for validating a user password. For your own use case, you can decide to use a different script.if (newPassword != confirmPassword) { return 'passwords are different';
}
if (newPassword.lenght &lt; 7) { return 'password must be at least 10 symbols';
}
return null;
